SIMPLE: inflate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inflate
<hw>In*flate"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>p. a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>inflatus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>inflare</ets> to inflate; pref.
<ets>in-</ets> in + <ets>flare</ets> to blow. See <er>Blow</er> to puff
wind.]</ety> <def>Blown in; inflated.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Inflate
<hw>In*flate"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Inflated</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Inflating</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To swell or distend
with air or gas; to dilate; to expand; to enlarge; <as>as, to
<ex>inflate</ex> a bladder; to <ex>inflate</ex> the
lungs.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When passion's tumults in the bosom rise,⟦br⟧
<qex>Inflate</qex> the features, and enrage the eyes.</q> <rj><qau>J.
Scott of Amwell.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: To swell; to puff up; to elate; <as>as, to
<ex>inflate</ex> one with pride or vanity</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Inflate</qex> themselves with some insane delight.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to become unduly expanded or increased;
<as>as, to <ex>inflate</ex> the currency</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Inflate
<hw>In*flate"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To expand; to fill; to
distend.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inflated</ent>⟦br⟧
